48    /**
49    * This pass identifies all global names, simple (e.g. <code>a</code>) or
50    * qualified (e.g. <code>a.b.c</code>), and the dependencies between them, then
51    * removes code associated with unreferenced names. It starts by assuming that
52    * only externally accessible names (e.g. <code>window</code>) are referenced,
53    * then iteratively marks additional names as referenced (e.g. <code>Foo</code>
54    * in <code>window['foo'] = new Foo();</code>). This makes it possible to
55    * eliminate code containing circular references.
56    *
57    * <p>Qualified names can be defined using dotted or object literal syntax
58    * (<code>a.b.c = x;</code> or <code>a.b = {c: x};</code>, respectively).
59    *
60    * <p>Removal of prototype classes is currently all or nothing. In other words,
61    * prototype properties and methods are never individually removed.
62    *
63    * <p>Optionally generates pretty HTML output of data so that it is easy to
64    * analyze dependencies.
65    *
66    * <p>Only operates on names defined in the global scope, but it would be easy
67    * to extend the pass to names defined in local scopes.
68    *
69    * TODO(nicksantos): In the initial implementation of this pass, it was
70    * important to understand namespaced names (e.g., that a.b is distinct from
71    * a.b.c). Now that this pass comes after CollapseProperties, this is no longer
72    * necessary. For now, I've changed so that {@code referenceParentNames}
73    * creates a two-way reference between a.b and a.b.c, so that they're
74    * effectively the same name. When someone has the time, we should completely
75    * rip out all the logic that understands namespaces.
76    *
77    */

481    /**
482    * <p>Identifies all dependency scopes.
483    *
484    * <p>A dependency scope is a relationship between a node tree and a name that
485    * implies that the node tree will not execute (and thus can be eliminated) if
486    * the name is never referenced.
487    *
488    * <p>The entire parse tree is ultimately in a dependency scope relationship
489    * with <code>window</code> (or an equivalent name for the global scope), but
490    * the goal here is to find finer-grained relationships. This callback creates
491    * dependency scopes for every assignment statement, variable declaration, and
492    * function call in the global scope.
493    *
494    * <p>Note that dependency scope node trees aren't necessarily disjoint.
495    * In the following code snippet, for example, the function definition
496    * forms a dependency scope with the name <code>f</code> and the assignment
497    * inside the function forms a dependency scope with the name <code>x</code>.
498    * <pre>
499    * var x; function f() { x = 1; }
500    * </pre>
501    */

1324    /**
1325    * The NameAnalyzer algorithm works best when all objects have a canonical
1326    * name in the global scope. When multiple names in the global scope
1327    * point to the same object, things start to break down.
1328    *
1329    * For example, if we have
1330    * <code>
1331    * var a = {};
1332    * var b = a;
1333    * a.foo = 3;
1334    * alert(b.foo);
1335    * </code>
1336    * then a.foo and b.foo are the same name, even though NameAnalyzer doesn't
1337    * represent them as such.
1338    *
1339    * To handle this case, we look at all the aliases in the program.
1340    * If descendant properties of that alias are assigned, then we create a
1341    * directional reference from the original name to the alias. For example,
1342    * in this case, the assign to {@code a.foo} triggers a reference from
1343    * {@code b} to {@code a}, but NOT from a to b.
1344    *
1345    * Similarly, "instanceof" checks do not prevent the removal
1346    * of a unaliased name but an instanceof check on an alias can only be removed
1347    * if the other aliases are also removed, so we add a connection here.
1348    */
